dollars.

12:49.402 --> 12:54.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is motivating the rise of
fake news,
and what tools are tech
companies developing

12:54.273 --> 12:56.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to stop its spread?

12:56.042 --> 12:59.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As part of a series of
conversations, I'm
joined by Marc Fisher of The
Washington Post,

12:59.846 --> 13:05.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who wrote one of the deeper
dives into how
this baseless story spread so
fast and how

13:05.284 --> 13:07.086 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it almost ended in tragedy.

13:07.120 --> 13:11.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Marc, this is one of the first
stories that
I think drew a connection for
people that

13:11.090 --> 13:13.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
virtual hoaxes have real-world
consequences.

13:13.826 --> 13:15.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARC FISHER, The Washington
Post: Well, they
absolutely do.

13:15.628 --> 13:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we saw this when a gunman
walked into
the pizza place that was the
subject of this

13:20.667 --> 13:27.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
false rumor about a supposed sex
ring that
Hillary Clinton and John
Podesta, her campaign

13:27.040 --> 13:31.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chairman, were running in a
residential neighborhood
pizza place in Washington, D.C.

13:31.978 --> 13:36.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we were able to do was
to kind of
trace this back to patient zero,
looking back

13:36.249 --> 13:39.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to, how did this spread and why
did it spread?

13:39.485 --> 13:44.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And what we found was a
combination of people
who had a profit motive and
people who were

13:44.090 --> 13:49.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really quite innocently running
across this
story and deciding that it was
concerning

13:49.095 --> 13:51.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to them and they wanted to know
more about
it.

13:51.297 --> 13:54.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That's one of
the things
people are going to wonder
about.

13:54.300 --> 13:57.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you not see the falsehood
in this?

13:57.537 --> 13:59.405 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Or how do you press share?

13:59.439 --> 14:03.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or how do you end up kind of
perpetrating
this lie further and further?

14:03.943 --> 14:05.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What were the answers that
people were giving
you?

14:05.745 --> 14:09.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARC FISHER: You know, I think
there is a
tendency to dismiss the people
who spread

14:09.882 --> 14:15.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these stories as uneducated or
simply not
understanding the technology
they're dealing

14:15.388 --> 14:16.355 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
with.

14:16.389 --> 14:17.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Anything but the case.

14:17.390 --> 14:19.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They tend to be quite educated
people.

14:19.258 --> 14:22.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They tend to be people who are
very well-connected
online.

14:22.862 --> 14:28.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they're stumbling into
sometimes,
first of all, there's kind of a
loss of trust.

14:28.201 --> 14:32.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you look at the whole
diminution of
trust across society about
government, about

14:32.872 --> 14:37.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the news media, people are
looking for alternative
ideas and alternative sources.

14:37.810 --> 14:42.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's why they are open to
these kinds of
stories that they find online.

14:42.148 --> 14:46.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, once they find them,
what I found
in talking to the people who
spread the message

14:46.185 --> 14:50.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most widely is that they were
kind of caught
up in the fun of this.

14:50.456 --> 14:55.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To them, it was kind of a game,
a serious
game, because they thought they
were saving

14:55.061 --> 15:00.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children who were being held in
this underground
sex ring, but kind of a game,
where they were

15:00.133 --> 15:02.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
really enjoying the hunt.

15:02.802 --> 15:08.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that thrill of the chase is
really very
similar to what's most
satisfying about doing

15:08.641 --> 15:11.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
journalism, but without the
responsibility
part.

15:11.277 --> 15:16.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the part where they
say, well -- you
know, it's reminiscent of what
Silicon Valley

15:16.449 --> 15:21.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
executives used to say years
ago, that the
Internet is a self-correcting
mechanism.

15:21.120 --> 15:25.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the people who were
involved in this
believe that, and they're really
not keeping

15:25.725 --> 15:30.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it front of mind the real-world
damage, such
as a gunman showing up to
conduct his own

15:30.963 --> 15:32.698 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
investigation.

15:32.732 --> 15:35.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, what
you're kind of
describing is almost a
large-scale game of

15:35.601 --> 15:37.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
"Clue" being played by thousands
of people.

15:37.203 --> 15:38.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm aging myself with the
reference to that
game.

15:38.938 --> 15:42.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But tell us a little bit more
about the people
who are doing this for a profit
motive.

15:42.341 --> 15:44.811 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARC FISHER: Well, there is that
side of things.

15:44.844 --> 15:48.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so some people are doing it
for political
reasons and some people are
doing it for profit.

15:48.815 --> 15:55.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you find some of these -- an
extraordinary
amount of the traffic online
about Pizzagate,

15:55.354 --> 16:00.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this rumor, was going through
odd places,
Vietnam, Macedonia.

16:00.660 --> 16:07.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's going on there is that
people are setting
up sites and setting up bots,
which are essentially

16:07.900 --> 16:14.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
algorithms that are used to
spread a message
or to retweet something many,
many times.

16:14.140 --> 16:19.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they do this because the
more they can
get people coming to their site,
the more

16:19.979 --> 16:24.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advertising revenue they get
from the big
social media companies.

16:24.650 --> 16:31.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there is a profit that can be
made by taking
something, however fantastic or
incredible,

16:31.791 --> 16:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and putting it out there in such
a way that
it goes viral, and then all of
that Web traffic,

16:36.429 --> 16:39.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all of those clicks turn out to
-- translate
into dollars.

16:39.398 --> 16:43.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, just
recently, Facebook
and Google tried to take a
little bit of those

16:43.936 --> 16:46.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dollar incentives away from
these fake news
sites.

16:46.606 --> 16:48.908 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, other than that, what else
are they doing?

16:48.941 --> 16:50.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What else can they do?

16:50.209 --> 16:52.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARC FISHER: Well, they can do a
lot more
than they're doing.

16:52.578 --> 16:56.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the reason we're able to say
that is,
we look across the ocean to
Europe, where

16:56.148 --> 17:02.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they are doing more, under
pressure from governments
there that don't have our same
system of First

17:02.255 --> 17:07.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amendment guarantees and don't
have the kind
of freedom that our Internet
companies have

17:07.994 --> 17:13.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a result of the exemption
that absolves
them from responsibility for the
content that

17:13.933 --> 17:15.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they have on their sites.

17:15.534 --> 17:18.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's from the 1996
Telecommunications Act.

17:18.437 --> 17:23.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Europe, without those legal
strictures,
there is a different kind of
legal system

17:23.242 --> 17:29.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
involved where these companies
are now being
required to remove derogatory
material about

17:29.181 --> 17:31.083 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people from their sites.

17:31.117 --> 17:32.518 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're having to do that.

17:32.551 --> 17:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they clearly know how to do
that.

17:34.553 --> 17:39.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They choose not to in this
country, in part
because it's very expensive to
have editors

17:39.258 --> 17:44.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and producers going through and
making sure
that the material that is on
their site is

17:44.196 --> 17:45.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
responsible.

17:46.032 --> 17:50.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Internet companies tend to
say, that is
not our responsibility, this is
purely a matter

17:50.336 --> 17:54.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
for the users to express
themselves however
they wish.

17:54.407 --> 17:58.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you think about the rest
of our economy,
there is no other product, there
is no other

17:58.277 --> 18:03.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
news product or even physical
product where
the maker says, we have no
responsibility

18:03.950 --> 18:05.518 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for what we make.

18:05.551 --> 18:07.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is just the nature of our
commerce.

18:07.820 --> 18:10.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We expect companies that produce
things to
take responsibility.

18:10.923 --> 18:13.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how does
it change the
landscape of journalism?

18:13.626 --> 18:18.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is definitely a line of
thought that
says just by us labeling this --
quote, unquote

18:18.531 --> 18:22.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- "fake news," instead of
outright lies or
conspiracy theories, that we're
elevating

18:22.768 --> 18:25.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it to a status of respect and
credibility
that it doesn't deserve.

18:25.438 --> 18:30.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, the idea of yellow
journalism has
existed since the late 1800s.

18:30.443 --> 18:33.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It helped us get into the
Spanish-American
War.

18:33.579 --> 18:35.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARC FISHER: Sure.

18:35.114 --> 18:38.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And conspiracy theories have
been around since
the dawn of civilization.

18:38.451 --> 18:41.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's biblical admonitions
against them.

18:41.220 --> 18:44.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so that's always been there,
probably
always will be.

18:44.123 --> 18:49.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the problem is not really
the fake news
or the speech itself.

18:49.095 --> 18:51.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The problem is the way it's
being spread.

18:51.297 --> 18:56.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's being spread more quickly
and more widely
through technology than ever
before.

18:56.736 --> 18:58.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's the part that we
haven't gotten
a handle on.

18:58.971 --> 19:00.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, what is the role for
traditional journalism?

19:00.840 --> 19:06.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, fact-checking,
obviously trying
to build up our credibility, so
that people

19:06.746 --> 19:10.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do see that there are places
that can be trusted.

19:10.049 --> 19:15.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we do happen to live in a
time when trust
is at a relative low.

19:15.721 --> 19:20.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have seen this in periods
of economic
trouble and political trouble in
our country,

19:20.359 --> 19:25.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after the Kennedy assassination
and now after
the 2008 crash.

19:25.264 --> 19:30.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, during those periods,
people do look
for alternative sources, and
that's what's

19:30.469 --> 19:32.271 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happening now.

19:32.304 --> 19:34.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Marc Fisher of
The Washington Post, one of many
conversations

19:34.707 --> 19:36.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we will be having on this topic.

19:36.509 --> 19:42.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thanks so much for joining us.

19:42.782 --> 19:46.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARC FISHER: Thank you.

