camp at Parris Island, South
Carolina.

20:25.891 --> 20:30.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's one of the few young women
who want
to enter the combat positions
that for years

20:30.229 --> 20:32.198 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have been shut to women.

20:32.231 --> 20:36.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She wants to be an air defense
gunner, to
shoot Stinger missiles.

20:36.268 --> 20:40.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, first, it's the basics of
knife-fighting.

20:40.172 --> 20:47.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Hey, we see how slashing
that partner
right down the center of their
chest, right?

20:47.313 --> 20:48.280 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARINE RECRUITS: Yes, sir!

20:48.314 --> 20:49.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Vertical slash!

20:49.615 --> 20:52.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: These early
weeks of boot
camp are tough.

20:52.151 --> 20:54.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Recruits are still getting used
to the rigors
of Marine training.

20:54.987 --> 20:59.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't sleep much, and many
haven't been
away from home for this long.

20:59.358 --> 21:02.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Recruit Wolff admits she's
having a hard time.

21:02.061 --> 21:04.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I know it's still early in your
training.

21:04.063 --> 21:05.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you feel like you're
doing?

21:05.531 --> 21:10.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REBEKAH WOLFF, Marine Corps
Recruit: I feel
like I could do better.

21:10.769 --> 21:17.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was a lot better at home,
probably because
I get a lot more sleep and I eat
a lot more

21:17.710 --> 21:19.078 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than what I do here.

21:19.111 --> 21:21.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: What have you
been telling
mom and dad back home?

21:21.347 --> 21:26.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REBEKAH WOLFF: In all honesty, I
tell my mom
and dad that I want to come home
and that

21:26.552 --> 21:27.953 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I can't wait to see them.

21:27.987 --> 21:30.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: If you could
choose, would
you go home right now?

21:30.256 --> 21:31.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
REBEKAH WOLFF: No, sir.

21:31.757 --> 21:34.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I came here to become a Marine.

21:34.426 --> 21:36.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I'm going to leave as a
Marine.

21:36.395 --> 21:41.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We met two
other female
recruits who also want to go
into these newly

21:41.233 --> 21:43.936 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
opened combat positions.

21:43.969 --> 21:47.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Twenty-one-year-old Victoria
Golab-Meyer wants
to be a combat engineer.

21:47.173 --> 21:49.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICTORIA GOLAB-MEYER, Marine
Corps Recruit:
And the fact that there's so
many women now

21:49.608 --> 21:56.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are excited to try it and
know that women
have a place somewhere, it's
worth fighting

21:56.682 --> 21:58.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for, to say the least.

21:58.617 --> 22:03.522 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And
18-year-old Lacey Elkins
wants to operate a tank or an
amphibious assault

22:03.556 --> 22:05.257 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
vehicle.

22:05.291 --> 22:09.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LACEY ELKINS, Marine Corps
Recruit: I like
to experience new things, and I
don't like

22:09.094 --> 22:10.062 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
being comfortable.

22:10.095 --> 22:12.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Comfortable just kind of sets
you nowhere.

22:12.231 --> 22:17.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: As we reported
previously,
the Marines didn't want women
serving in certain

22:17.603 --> 22:22.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
combat positions, arguing it
would make them
a less effective fighting force.

22:22.107 --> 22:24.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they were overruled by the
secretary of
defense.

22:24.977 --> 22:30.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the Marines say orders are
orders, and
they're now working hard to
integrate women.

22:30.282 --> 22:35.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One thing they have done is to
establish physical
standards for each combat
position, and they

22:35.221 --> 22:39.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are the same for men and women,
one standard
that everyone has to meet.

22:39.925 --> 22:41.427 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

22:41.460 --> 22:43.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT NELLER, Marine Corps
Commandant: This
is physically demanding stuff.

22:43.462 --> 22:46.699 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, we're talking carrying
heavy loads.

22:46.732 --> 22:47.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're not riding around.

22:47.800 --> 22:48.767 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We're walking.

22:48.801 --> 22:51.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Marine Corps infantry is
light infantry.

22:51.403 --> 22:53.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And the load is heavy.

22:53.472 --> 22:57.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: General Robert
Neller is
the commandant of the Marine
Corps, the service's

22:57.576 --> 22:59.545 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
highest military officer.

22:59.578 --> 23:04.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says equal standards for men
and women
is an important step to making
integration

23:04.917 --> 23:05.884 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
work.

23:05.918 --> 23:07.686 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

23:07.720 --> 23:09.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT NELLER: It doesn't matter
who you are,
where you're from, how much
money you have

23:09.989 --> 23:12.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
got, the color of your skin,
your religion.

23:12.224 --> 23:14.493 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Nobody cares.

23:14.526 --> 23:21.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's two types of people in
combat, those
that can, and those that you
worry about.

23:21.166 --> 23:22.901 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's it.

23:22.935 --> 23:27.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And if women
pass those
standards and meet all those
requirements,

23:27.172 --> 23:28.140 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you're not worried about them?

23:28.173 --> 23:29.141 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

23:29.174 --> 23:30.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT NELLER: No.

23:30.175 --> 23:31.143 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They're Marines.

23:31.176 --> 23:32.144 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Do your job.

23:32.177 --> 23:34.046 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SGT.

23:34.079 --> 23:35.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CODY MORRIS, Marine Corps: How
quickly you
move directly translates to
their survivability.

23:35.748 --> 23:39.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Combat veteran
Sergeant
Cody Morris oversees basic
warrior training

23:39.852 --> 23:41.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at Parris Island.

23:41.253 --> 23:45.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says equal standards are
crucial, but he
worries they won't last.

23:45.958 --> 23:51.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He echoed a concern we heard
from many, that
if enough women don't pass these
standards,

23:51.297 --> 23:52.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they will be lowered.

23:52.531 --> 23:54.199 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SGT.

23:54.233 --> 23:56.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CODY MORRIS: I guarantee the
transition and
them being able to mesh together
would be

23:56.802 --> 24:01.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot easier if we knew that,
oh, you completed
a 20-mile hike with this much
weight and this

24:01.707 --> 24:02.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
much time?

24:02.708 --> 24:03.876 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So did I.

24:03.909 --> 24:05.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's what matters most to
the people
that I know.

24:05.678 --> 24:08.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It isn't so much that you're a
male and I'm
a female and you're this and
you're that.

24:08.747 --> 24:13.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's that the mission is hard,
and I need
everybody to be able to
accomplish it, and

24:13.118 --> 24:15.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not just to meet some diversity
criteria.

24:15.087 --> 24:20.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We talked with
some current
Marines and some former Marines
who say, OK,

24:20.059 --> 24:23.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these jobs are now open to
women, and that
somewhere down the road there's
going to be

24:23.529 --> 24:29.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some pressure brought to bear on
the Corps
to lower those standards to
guarantee that

24:29.435 --> 24:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more women get into these jobs.

24:31.537 --> 24:32.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that going to happen?

24:32.538 --> 24:33.505 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

24:33.539 --> 24:35.341 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBERT NELLER: Not on my watch.

24:35.374 --> 24:39.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have heard the secretary of
defense and
the secretary of the Navy say,
we're not going

24:39.278 --> 24:40.245 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to lower the standard.

24:40.279 --> 24:42.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have established the
standards.

24:42.614 --> 24:44.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They know what the standards
are.

24:44.316 --> 24:49.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if any standard we set was
causing high
attrition or high injury rate of
anybody,

24:49.121 --> 24:50.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then that's probably something
you want to
look at.

24:50.789 --> 24:52.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, right now, that's not the
case.

24:52.758 --> 24:57.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So far, of the
12,000 women
who've enlisted in the Marines
in the last

24:57.563 --> 25:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
three years, only 150 have
chosen to apply
for these combat jobs.

25:01.934 --> 25:07.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And of those, only 53 about, one
in three,
passed these tougher standards.

25:07.973 --> 25:11.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The rest failed, dropped out or
are still
in training.

25:11.643 --> 25:15.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More broadly, women also get
injured more
often than men at boot camp, and
they drop

25:15.948 --> 25:19.284 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out at double the rate of men.

25:19.318 --> 25:25.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To some, this is all evidence
that putting
women into combat roles is a bad
idea.

25:25.157 --> 25:28.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Retired Colonel Mary Reinwald
spent 27 years
in the Marines.

25:28.861 --> 25:31.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She now edits "Leatherneck"
magazine, a magazine
for the Marine community.

25:31.997 --> 25:33.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

25:33.799 --> 25:35.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARY REINWALD (RET.), Marine
Corps: Women
break, physically break down at
a much greater

25:35.768 --> 25:37.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
level than our male
counterparts.

25:37.536 --> 25:38.704 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's just reality.

25:38.737 --> 25:42.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can a -- women carry the same
load as a man?

25:42.141 --> 25:47.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And loads in Iraq and
Afghanistan were as
much as 70, 80 pounds, if not
more, depending

25:47.112 --> 25:48.113 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on what the mission was.

25:48.147 --> 25:49.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: That's the
full battle gear.

25:49.114 --> 25:50.482 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

25:50.516 --> 25:52.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY REINWALD: That's the full
battle gear,
and more in some cases.

25:52.718 --> 25:56.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, how long would I have
lasted with
something like that, again, as
much heart

25:56.155 --> 25:57.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as I may have had?

25:57.656 --> 25:58.690 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But that's really not the issue.

25:58.724 --> 26:00.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's, when did my body start to
break down?

26:00.459 --> 26:01.427 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

26:01.460 --> 26:03.228 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

26:03.262 --> 26:05.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATE GERMANO (RET.), Marine
Corps: I would
say that if there's one woman
out of 1,000

26:05.063 --> 26:10.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who can make that move and move
into the ground
combat job, then why should she
be denied

26:10.068 --> 26:11.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that opportunity?

26:11.870 --> 26:14.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Retired
Lieutenant Colonel
Kate Germano commanded the
female battalion

26:14.807 --> 26:20.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at Parris Island, but she was
fired in 2015
for creating a -- quote --
"hostile command

26:20.045 --> 26:21.213 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
climate."

26:21.246 --> 26:24.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She says she was pushing to
improve recruit
training.

26:24.082 --> 26:29.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She says the reason so many
women drop out
and so many fail to pass the new
combat standards

26:29.888 --> 26:34.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is that the Marines haven't
raised the bar
high enough for women.

26:34.193 --> 26:40.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you would argue that it's
lowered expectations
of women over the years that has
driven this

26:40.933 --> 26:45.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
disparity, not some inherent
inability on
behalf of women?

26:45.070 --> 26:46.038 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

26:46.071 --> 26:47.539 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

26:47.573 --> 26:49.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATE GERMANO: Absolutely,
absolutely lowered
expectations for females.

26:49.241 --> 26:52.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I would say is that
there is a lot
of data to support that
conclusion.

26:52.845 --> 26:58.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: As proof,
Germano says she
was able to dramatically improve
female marksmanship

26:58.450 --> 26:59.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at Parris Island.

26:59.451 --> 27:00.419 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

27:00.452 --> 27:02.287 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

27:02.321 --> 27:05.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATE GERMANO: We were able to
take an initial
qualification rate of 67 percent
for the women,

27:05.257 --> 27:08.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
compared to high 80s and 90
percent for male
workers.

27:08.961 --> 27:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were able to take that low
percentage and
bring it to right under 92
percent in less

27:14.466 --> 27:15.434 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than a year.

27:15.467 --> 27:18.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that was not through any
extra training.

27:18.337 --> 27:24.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It wasn't through any
pre-recruit training,
screening.

27:24.076 --> 27:29.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was strictly through changing
the expectation
that women could shoot and that
they should

27:29.448 --> 27:31.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be expected to shoot well.

27:31.483 --> 27:35.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Germano says
those high
expectations should trickle down
to better

27:35.854 --> 27:40.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conditioning of recruits before
boot camp,
like we saw Rebekah Wolff doing
here this

27:40.559 --> 27:44.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
summer, as well as recruiting
stronger women
to begin with.

27:44.263 --> 27:45.230 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SGT.

27:45.264 --> 27:46.632 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MAJ.

27:46.665 --> 27:48.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANGELA MANESS, Marine Corps: We
have to look
for a better product.

27:48.467 --> 27:53.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
America has to look and give us
what we're
looking for here, and that's a
college athlete.

27:53.238 --> 27:57.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Sergeant Major
Angela Maness,
the highest ranking enlisted
officer at Parris

27:57.709 --> 28:02.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Island, says the Marines are
setting high
standards and have started a new
initiative

28:02.314 --> 28:03.482 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to recruit stronger women.

28:03.515 --> 28:04.483 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SGT.

28:04.516 --> 28:06.418 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MAJ.

28:06.451 --> 28:08.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA MANESS: So, when we have
a solid foundation
coming here already, with muscle
already attached

28:08.987 --> 28:13.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to her body, it's not going to
be that difficult
to get her trained to the level
that we need

28:13.926 --> 28:15.694 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
her.

28:15.727 --> 28:18.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A few weeks
after we first
met the three recruits, we
checked back at

28:18.564 --> 28:19.698 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
boot camp.

28:19.731 --> 28:22.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, something is different since
the last
time I saw you.

28:22.534 --> 28:25.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LACEY ELKINS: Yes, I became a
United States
Marine.

